            "answer_text": "The expression was first used in writing by Thomas Carlyle, in The French Revolution, 1837: \"Arrestment, sudden really as a bolt out of the Blue, has hit strange victims.\"  Carlyle being a learned man conversant with Latin and Greek authors, the phrase was very likely derived from Ode 34 by the Roman poet Horace, from the second stanza, lines 2 and 3 (\"splits the clouds with his flashing lightning\"):  cogor relictos: namque Diespiter, igni corusco nubila dividens plerumque, per purum tonantis egit equos volucremque currum\u2026 ",
